GUIDANCE AND MANAGEMENT TECHNIQUES\ulnone :\par
\ul\par
\ulnone All employees of the extended care will adhere to the specifications of rule 2-12-22 in the Child Care Licensing Center rules.  Child guidance and management measures must be developmentally appropriate for the child, shall be consistent, and shall be explained to the child.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\nowidctlpar\cf0\kerning0 The following techniques or practices may be used by Staff.  Any technique or practice used shall be developmentally appropriate, consistent and shall occur at the time of the incident.\par
-Setting clear limits\par
-Redirecting to an appropriate activity\par
-Showing positive alternatives\par
-Modeling the desired behavior\par
-Reinforcing appropriate behavior\par
-encouraging children to control their own behavior, cooperate with others and solve problems by talking\par
-Separation from the situation, shall last no more than one minute per each year of the child\rquote s age.  Upon the child\rquote s return to the activity, the provider shall review the reason for the separation and discuss the expected behavior with the child\par
-Holding a child for a short period of time, such as a protective hug, so that the child may regain self-control\par
\par
The following are prohibited discipline techniques\par
-Abuse, endanger, or neglect of a child, including shaking\par
-Utilize cruel, harsh, unusual, or extreme techniques\par
-Utilize any form of corporal punishment\par
-Delegate children to manage or disciple other children\par
-Use physical restraints on a child\par
-Restrain a child by any means other than holding child for a short period of time, \par
-Place a child in a locked room or confine child in any enclosed area\par
-Confine child to equipment such as cribs or high charis\par
-Humiliate, threaten or frighten children\par
-Subject children to profane language or verbal abuse\par
-Make derogatory or sarcastic remarks about children or their families\par
-Punish children for failure to eat or sleep or for toileting accidents\par
-Withhold any food beverages or water, rest or toilet use\par
-Punish an entire group of children due to the unacceptable behavior of one\par
-Isolate and restrict children from any or all activities for an extended period of time.\par

\pard\nowidctlpar\cf1\kerning28\par
\par
 Also, all staff members will seek to cultivate self-discipline and socially-acceptable behavior in each child.  At the beginning of the year, simple, important rules and limits will be implemented, designed to protect the child and the group.  Staff will be positive and focus on \ldblquote do\rquote s\rdblquote  rather than \ldblquote do not\rquote s\rdblquote  when redirecting inappropriate behavior and use constant praise when the child engages in appropriate behavior.  When there is a discipline problem in the classroom, the following procedures will be observed:\par
\par

\pard\nowidctlpar\fi-360\li720\tx720 1.\tab The child will first be given a verbal warning and reminded of the specific rule he/she has disobeyed.  \par
2.\tab If the negative behavior continues after a warning, then the child will be placed in a chair for \ldblquote time out\rdblquote  and again reminded of the specific rule.  \par
3.\tab If \ldblquote time out\rdblquote  fails to correct the behavior, the child will be removed from the classroom to sit in the preschool office with the director, who will again talk to the child.\par
4.\tab If the problem continues, the director will contact the parents, inform them of the situation, and request that they pick up the child immediately.\par
5.\tab If the child continues to act in a negative behavior on a regular or frequent basis, then the director will have a meeting with the parents to create a disciplinary plan specifically tailored for the child. \par
6.\tab If a child still chooses to misbehave following the disciplinary plan implementation, he/she may be removed from participation in the program by a joint decision of the director and the preschool elder.\par

