MANAGEMENT OF ILLNESS POLICIES\ulnone :\par
\ul\par

\pard\keepn\nowidctlpar\cf0\kerning0\ulnone All Staff members are required to take six hours of communicable disease training.  This training helps Staff members to avoid and manage the spread of disease. If a communicable disease is found, the director will notify the entire class within four hours.\par
\par
Management of Illness\par
A. If a child has any of the following symptoms, the staff member is to bring the child to the preschool office immediately.  The director will then call the parent and supervise the child until the parent comes to pick up the child.\par
-Temperature of at least 100 degrees Fahrenheit when in combination with any other sign or symptom of illness\par
-Diarrhea (two times)\par
-Severe coughing, causing the child to become red or blue in the face or to make a whooping sound\par
-Difficult or rapid breathing\par
-Yellowish skin or eyes\par
-Redness of the eye or eyelid, thick pus eye discharge, matted eyelashes, burning, itching or eye pain\par
-Untreated infected skin patches, unusual spots or rashes\par
-Unusually dark urine and or gray or white stool\par
-Stiff neck with elevated temperature\par
-Evidence of untreated lice, scabies, or other parasitic infestations\par
-Sore throat or difficulty in swallowing\par
-Vomiting more than one time or when accompanied by any other sign or symptom of illness\par
\par
*\cf1\kerning28  If your child\rquote s temperature is 100.0 degrees F or greater (or 1 or 2 degrees above the child\rquote s normal temperature) (s)he should remain home until (s)he has been fever free for 24 hours without the use of fever reducer medication (acetaminophen \endash  i.e. Tylenol or ibuprofen \endash  i.e. Advil or Motrin). Remember fever is a symptom indicating the presence of an illness.  Also, if your child has vomitted, (s)he may not return to preschool until 24 hours have past.\cf0\kerning0\par
